<section xml:id="section-adding-and-subtracting-polynomials">
  <title>Adding and Subtracting Polynomials</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-add-subtract-multiply-square-polynomials" text="local">MTH 65 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-fU6NluIfNnsbsnRi9Ril6M" />
    </figure>

    <p>
      A <term>polynomial</term> is a type of algebraic expression with certain features we will
      describe below.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            A company's sales, <m>s</m> (in millions of dollars), can be modeled by <m>2.2t+5.8</m>,
            where <m>t</m> stands for the number of years since <m>2010</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            An object is launched upward from the top of a building and its height, <m>h</m> (in
            feet), can be modeled by <m>-16t^2+32t+300</m>, where <m>t</m> represents the amount of
            time (in seconds) since the launch.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The volume <m>V</m> (in cubic inches) of an open-top box with a square base can be
            calculated by <m>30s^2-\frac{1}{2}s^3</m>, where <m>s</m> stands for the length of the
            square base, and the box sides have to be cut from a certain square piece of metal.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      All of the expressions above are polynomials. In this section, we will learn some basic
      vocabulary relating to polynomials and we'll then learn how to add and subtract polynomials.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Polynomial Vocabulary</title>
    <p>
      We start this section with a flood of vocabulary associated with polynomials.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="definition-polynomial">                                                               <idx><h>polynomial</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>terms of</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>polynomial</term> is an expression with one or more
          <xref ref="definition-term" text="custom">terms</xref> added together. A term of a
          polynomial must either be a number or the product of a number and one or more variables
          raised to natural number powers.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Here are three polynomials: <m>x^2-5x+2</m>, <m>t^3-1</m>, and <m>7y</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The expression <m>3x^4y^3+7xy^2-12xy</m> is an example of a polynomial in more than
              one variable.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The polynomial <m>x^2-5x+3</m> has three terms: <m>x^2</m>, <m>-5x</m>, and <m>3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The polynomial <m> 3x^4+7xy^2-12xy</m> also has three terms.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The polynomial <m>t^3-1</m> has two terms.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      A polynomial will never have a variable raised to a negative power, raised to a fractional
      power, in an exponent, in the denominator of a fraction, or under a radical. The following
      terms could never be part of polynomial: <m>x^{-3}</m>, <m>x^{4/5}</m>, <m>3^x</m>,
      <m>\frac{2}{x}</m>, <m>5\sqrt{x}</m>.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="definition-coefficient">                                                              <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>coefficients</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>coefficient</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>coefficient</term> (aka numerical coefficient) of a term is the numerical factor
          of that term.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              The coefficient of the term <m>\frac{4}{3}x^6</m> is <m>\frac{4}{3}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The coefficient of the second term of the polynomial <m>x^2-5x+3</m> is <m>-5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The coefficient of the term <m>\frac{y^7}{4}</m> is <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>parserPopUp.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
        <pg-code>
          $yes = DropDown(['is', 'is not'],0);
          $no  = DropDown(['is', 'is not'],1);
        </pg-code>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Identify which of the following are polynomials and which are not.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>-2x^9-\frac{7}{13}x^3-1</m> <var name="$yes" form="popup"/> a
              polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is a polynomial.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>5x^{-2}-5x^2+3</m> <var name="$no" form="popup"/> a polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is not a polynomial because it has a negative exponent on a variable.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>\sqrt{2}x-\frac{3}{5}</m> <var name="$yes" form="popup"/> a
              polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is a polynomial. Note that <em>coefficients</em> can have radicals even though
              variables cannot, and the square root here is <em>only</em> applied to the <m>2</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>5x^3-5^{-5}x-x^4</m> <var name="$yes" form="popup"/> a polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is a polynomial.  Note that <em>coefficients</em> can have negative exponents
              even though variables cannot.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>\frac{25}{x^2}+23-x</m> <var name="$no" form="popup"/> a polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is not a polynomial because it has a variable in a denominator.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>37x^6-x+8^{\frac{4}{3}}</m> <var name="$yes" form="popup"/> a
              polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is a polynomial. Note that <em>coefficients</em> can have fractional exponents
              even though variables cannot.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>\sqrt{7x}-4x^3</m> <var name="$no" form="popup"/> a polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is not a polynomial because it has a variable inside a radical.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>6x^{\frac{3}{2}}+1</m> <var name="$no" form="popup"/> a polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is not a polynomial because a variable has a fractional exponent.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              The expression <m>6^x-3x^6</m> <var name="$no" form="popup"/> a polynomial.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              This is not a polynomial because it has a variable in an exponent.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </task>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <definition xml:id="definition-constant-term">                                                            <idx><h>constant term</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>constant term</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A term in a polynomial that doesn't have a variable factor is called a
          <term>constant term</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        The constant term of the polynomial <m>x^2-5x+3</m> is <m>3</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="definition-degree">                                                                   <idx><h>degree</h><h>of a term</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>degree of a term</term> is one way to measure how <q>large</q> it is.
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                When a term only has one variable, its degree is the exponent on that variable.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                When a term has more than one variable, its degree is the sum of the exponents on
                the variables. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The degree of a nonzero constant term is zero.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              The degree of <m>5x^2</m> is <m>2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The degree of <m>-\frac{4}{7}y^5</m> is <m>5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The degree of <m>-4x^2y^3</m> is <m>5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The degree of <m>17</m> is <m>0</m>. (Constant terms have degree <m>0</m> .)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="definition-degree-polynomial">                                                        <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>degree</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>degree</h><h>of a polynomial</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>degree of a nonzero polynomial</term> is the greatest degree that appears among
          its terms.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="definition-leading-term">                                                             <idx><h>leading term</h><h>of a polynomial</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>leading term</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>leading coefficient</h><h>of a polynomial</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>leading coefficient</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>leading term</term> of a polynomial is the term with the greatest degree
          (assuming there is no tie). The coefficient of a polynomial's leading term is called the
          polynomial's <term>leading coefficient</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        The degree of the polynomial <m>4x^2-5x+3</m> is <m>2</m> because the terms have degrees
        <m>2</m>, <m>1</m>, and <m>0</m>, respectively, and <m>2</m> is the largest. Its leading
        term is <m>4x^2</m>, and its leading coefficient is <m>4</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      To help us see a polynomial's degree quickly, it helps to write the terms in order from
      highest to lowest degree. When a polynomial's terms are written in this order, we say it is
      written in <term>standard form</term>. For example, we would change <m>7-4x-x^2</m> to
      <m>-x^2-4x+7</m> since <m>-x^2</m> is the leading term. By agreeing to write polynomials in
      standard form, we can look at the first term to quickly determine both the polynomial's degree
      and leading coefficient.
    </p>

    <p>
      There are special names for polynomials with a small number of terms, and for polynomials with
      certain degrees.
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>monomial</title>                                                                             <idx><h>monomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A polynomial with one term, such as <m>3x^5</m>, is called a monomial.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>binomial</title>                                                                             <idx><h>binomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A polynomial with two terms, such as <m>3x^5+2x</m>, is called a binomial.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>trinomial</title>                                                                            <idx><h>trinomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A polynomial with three terms, such as <m>x^2-5x+3</m>, is called a trinomial.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>constant polynomial</title>                                                                  <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>constant</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>constant polynomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A zero-degree polynomial is called a constant polynomial. An example is the polynomial
            <m>7</m>, which has degree zero.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>linear polynomial</title>                                                                    <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>linear</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>linear polynomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A first-degree polynomial is called a linear polynomial. An example is <m>-2x+7</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>quadratic polynomial</title>                                                                 <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>quadratic</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>quadratic polynomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A second-degree polynomial is called a quadratic polynomial. An example is
            <m>4x^2-2x+7</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>cubic polynomial</title>                                                                     <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>cubic</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>cubic polynomial</h></idx>
          <p>
            A third-degree polynomial is called a cubic polynomial. An example is
            <m>x^3+4x^2-2x+7</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
      Fourth-degree and fifth-degree polynomials are called quartic and quintic polynomials,                  <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>quartic</h></idx>
      respectively. If the degree of the polynomial, <m>n</m>, is greater than five, we'll simply             <idx><h>quartic polynomial</h></idx>
      call it an <m>n</m>th-degree polynomial. For example, the polynomial <m>5x^8-4x^5+1</m> is an           <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>quintic</h></idx>
      <m>8</m>th-degree polynomial.                                                                           <idx><h>quintic polynomial</h></idx>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Adding and Subtracting Polynomials</title>                                                         <idx><h>polynomial</h><h>addition and subtraction</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>addition</h><h>of polynomials</h></idx>
    <example xml:id="example-ketchup-production-costs">
      <title>Production Costs</title>
      <p>
        Bayani started a company that makes one-gallon ketchup jugs for industrial kitchens. The
        company's expenses only come from two things: supplies and labor. The cost of supplies,
        <m>S</m> (in thousands of dollars), can be modeled by <m>S=0.05x^2+2x+30</m>, where <m>x</m>
        is number of thousands of jugs of ketchup produced. The labor cost for his employees,
        <m>L</m> (in thousands of dollars), can be modeled by <m>0.1x^2+4x</m>, where <m>x</m> again
        represents the number of jugs they produce (in thousands of jugs). Find a model for the
        company's total production costs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since Bayani's company only has these two costs, we can find a model for the total
        production costs, <m>C</m> (in thousands of dollars), by adding the supply costs and the
        labor costs:
        <me>
          C=\left(0.05x^2+2x+30\right)+\left(0.1x^2+4x\right)
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        To finish simplifying our total production cost model, we'll combine the like terms:
        <md>
          <mrow>C \amp= 0.05x^2+0.1x^2+2x+4x+30</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= 0.15x^2+6x+30</mrow>
        </md>
        This simplified model can now calculate Bayani's total production costs <m>C</m> (in
        thousands of dollars) when the company produces <m>x</m> thousand jugs of ketchup.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      The process of adding two or more polynomials involves recognizing and then combining the like
      terms.
    </p>

    <exercise label="Contrib__PCC__BasicAlgebra__PolynomialBasics__PolyAddSubtract25.pg">
      <webwork source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/PolynomialBasics/PolyAddSubtract25.pg" seed="7"/>
    </exercise>

    <example xml:id="example-polyadd2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Simplify the expression
          <m>\left(\frac{1}{2}x^2-\frac{2}{3}x-\frac{3}{2}\right)+\left(\frac{3}{2}x^2+\frac{7}{2}x-\frac{1}{4}\right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\amp\left(\frac{1}{2}x^2\firsthighlight{{}-\frac{2}{3}x}\secondhighlight{{}-\frac{3}{2}}\right)+\left(\frac{3}{2}x^2\firsthighlight{{}+\frac{7}{2}x}\secondhighlight{{}-\frac{1}{4}}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\left(\frac{1}{2}x^2+\frac{3}{2}x^2\right)+\left(\firsthighlight{-\frac{2}{3}x+\frac{7}{2}x}\right)+\left(\secondhighlight{-\frac{3}{2}+\left(-\frac{1}{4}\right)}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \left(\frac{4}{2}x^2\right)+\left(\firsthighlight{-\frac{4}{6}x+\frac{21}{6}x}\right)+\left(\secondhighlight{-\frac{6}{4}+\left(-\frac{1}{4}\right)}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \left(2x^2\right)+\firsthighlight{\frac{17}{6}x}+\left(\secondhighlight{-\frac{7}{4}}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2x^2\firsthighlight{{}+\frac{17}{6}x}\secondhighlight{{}-\frac{7}{4}}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-profit-revenue-and-costs">
      <title>Profit, Revenue, and Costs</title>
      <p>
        From <xref ref="example-ketchup-production-costs"/>, we know Bayani's ketchup company's
        production costs, <m>C</m> (in thousands of dollars), for producing <m>x</m> thousand jugs
        of ketchup is modeled by <m>C=0.15x^2+6x+30</m>. The revenue, <m>R</m> (in thousands of
        dollars), from selling the ketchup can be modeled by <m>R=13x</m>, where <m>x</m> stands for
        the number of thousands of jugs of ketchup sold. The company's net profit can be calculated
        using the concept:
        <me>
          \text{net profit} = \text{revenue} - \text{costs}
        </me>
        Assuming all products produced will be sold, a polynomial to model the company's net profit,
        <m>P</m> (in thousands of dollars) is:
        <md>
          <mrow>P \amp= R-C</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= \left(13x\right)-\left(0.15x^2+6x+30\right)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= 13x-0.15x^2-6x-30</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp= -0.15x^2+\left(13x-6x\right)-30</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=-0.15x^2+7x-30</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      A very important difference between adding and subtracting polynomials is that when we
      subtract a polynomial, we must subtract <em>each term</em> in that polynomial.
    </p>
    <p>
      Notice that our first step in simplifying the expression in
      <xref ref="example-profit-revenue-and-costs"/> was to subtract <em>every</em> term in the
      second expression. We can also think of this as distributing a factor of <m>-1</m> across the
      second polynomial, <m>0.15x^2+6x+30</m>, and then adding these terms as follows:
      <md>
        <mrow>P \amp= R-C</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \left(13x\right)-\left(0.15x^2+6x+30\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \left(13x\right)+(-1)\left(0.15x^2+6x+30\right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 13x+(-1)0.15x^2+(-1)6x+(-1)30</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 13x-0.15x^2-6x-30</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= -0.15x^2+\left(13x-6x\right)-30</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=-0.15x^2+7x-30</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-poysub1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Subtract <m>\left(5x^3+4x^2-6x\right)-\left(-3x^2+9x-2\right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We must first subtract every term in <m>\left(-3x^2+9x-2\right)</m> from
          <m>\left(5x^3+4x^2-6x\right)</m>. Then we can combine like terms.
          <md>
            <mrow>\amp\left(5x^3+4x^2-6x\right)-\left(-3x^2+9x-2\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 5x^3+4x^2-6x \highlight{{}+{}} 3x^2 \highlight{{}-{}} 9x \highlight{{}+{}} 2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 5x^3+\left(4x^2+3x^2\right)+\left(-6x-9x\right)+2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 5x^3+7x^2-15x+2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise label="Contrib__PCC__BasicAlgebra__PolynomialBasics__PolyAddSubtract80.pg">
      <webwork source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/PolynomialBasics/PolyAddSubtract80.pg" seed="6"/>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      Let's look at one last example where the polynomial has multiple variables. Remember that like
      terms must have the same variable(s) with the same exponent(s).
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-polysub2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Subtract <m>\left( 3x^2y+8xy^2-17y^3 \right)-\left(2x^2y+11xy^2+4y^2 \right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Again, we'll begin by subtracting each term in <m>\left(2x^2y+11xy^2+4y^2\right)</m>.
          Once we've done this, we'll need to identify and combine like terms.
          <md>
            <mrow>\amp\left( 3x^2y+8xy^2-17y^3 \right)-\left(2x^2y+11xy^2+4y^2\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=
            3x^2y+8xy^2-17y^3 \highlight{{}-{}} 2x^2y \highlight{{}-{}} 11xy^2 \highlight{{}-{}} 4y^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\left(3x^2y-2x^2y\right)+\left(8xy^2-11xy^2\right)+\left(-17y^3-4y^2\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= x^2y-3xy^2-17y^3-4y^2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Evaluating Polynomial Expressions</title>
    <p>
      Evaluating expressions was introduced in
      <xref ref="section-variables-and-evaluating-expressions"/>, and involves replacing the
      variable(s) in an expression with specific numbers and calculating the result.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate the expression <m>C=0.15x^2+6x+30</m> from
          <xref ref="example-ketchup-production-costs"/> for <m>x=10</m> and explain what this means
          in context.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will replace <m>x</m> with <m>10</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>C\amp=0.15x^2+6x+30</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=0.15(\substitute{10})^2+6(\substitute{10})+30</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=0.15(100)+60+30</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=15+90</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=105</mrow>
          </md>
          The context was that <m>x</m> represents so many thousands of jugs of ketchup, and
          <m>C</m> represents the total cost, in thousands of dollars, to produce that many jugs. So
          in context, we can interpret this as it costs <m>\$105{,}000</m> to produce
          <m>10{,}000</m> jugs of ketchup.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      Recall that in <xref ref="subsection-evaluating-expressions-with-negative-numbers"/> and
      <xref ref="example-evaluating-expressions-with-negative-numbers"/> we discussed how
      <m>(-2)^2</m> and <m>-2^2</m> are not the same expressions. The first expression,
      <m>(-2)^2</m>, represents the number <m>-2</m> squared, and is <m>(-2)(-2)=4</m>. The second
      expression, <m>-2^2</m>, is the <em>opposite</em> of the number that you get after you square
      <m>2</m>, and is <m>-2^2=-(2\cdot 2) = -4</m>. So when substituting a negative number in for a
      variable, we recommend always using parentheses around that number.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate the expression <m>-12y^3+4y^2-9y+2</m> for <m>y=-5</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will replace <m>y</m> with <m>-5</m> and simplify the result:
          <md>
            <mrow>-12y^3+4y^2-9y+2 \amp= -12(\substitute{-5})^3+4(\substitute{-5})^2-9(\substitute{-5})+2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= -12(-125)+4(25)+45+2</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= 1647</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

