    <subexercises>
      <title>Applications</title>
      <exercisegroup cols="2">
        <title>Falling Object</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            The polynomial <m>\frac12gt^2+v_0t+h_0</m> gives the height of an object at time
            <m>t</m> (measured in seconds) when it is thrown straight up with an initial velocity
            <m>v_0</m> (measured in feet per second) from an initial height <m>h_0</m> (measured in
            feet) in a place where the acceleration from gravity is <m>g</m> (measured in feet per
            second per second). On Earth, the value of <m>g</m> is
            <m>-32\,\frac{\mathrm{ft}}{\mathrm{s}^2}</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="evaluate-falling-object-polynomial">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-evaluate-falling-object-polynomial">
            <pg-code>
              $t = random(1, 3, 0.1);
              $v0 = random(50, 70, 5);
              $h0 = random(4, 7, 1);
              $answer = NumberWithUnits(1/2*-32*$t^2 + $v0*$t + $h0, 'ft');
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                What is the height of an object on Earth <m><var name="$t"/></m> seconds after it is
                thrown straight up with an initial speed of <m><var name="$v0"/></m> feet per
                second from an initial height of <m><var name="$h0"/></m> feet?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$answer" width="16"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="evaluate-falling-object-polynomial-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-evaluate-falling-object-polynomial"/>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
      <exercisegroup cols="2">
        <title>Sum of Consecutive Integers</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            It turns out that if you add up all the whole numbers <m>1+2+3+\cdots+n</m>, the result
            is the polynomial <m>\frac12n^2+\frac12n</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-integers">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-integers">
            <pg-code>
              $n = random(500, 1000);
              $answer = Real($n*($n+1)/2);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                What is the result from adding <m>1+2+3+\cdots+<var name="$n"/></m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$answer" width="16"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-integers-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-integers"/>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
      <exercisegroup cols="2">
        <title>Sum of Consecutive Squares</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            It turns out that if you add up all the square numbers <m>1^2+2^2+3^2+\cdots+n^2</m>,
            the result is the polynomial <m>\frac13n^3 + \frac12n^2 + \frac16n</m>.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-squares">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-squares">
            <pg-code>
              $n = random(100, 200);
              $answer = Real($n*($n+1)*(2*$n+1)/6);
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                What is the result from adding <m>1^2+2^2+3^2+\cdots+<var name="$n"/>^2</m>?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$answer" width="16"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-squares-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-evaluate-sum-of-consecutive-squares"/>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
      <exercisegroup>
        <title>Sales and Costs</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            A company that sells a certain product can use polynomials to model its sales revenue
            (in dollars) and its costs (also in dollars). The variable <m>x</m> represents the
            number of units produced. Profit is revenue minus costs.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="sales-polyomials">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-sales-polyomials">
            <pg-code>
              @a = num_sort(random_subset(2, map {$_/10} (10 .. 60)));
              @b = num_sort(random_subset(2, map {$_/100} (100 .. 600)));
              @c = num_sort(random_subset(2, 1000 .. 6000));
              $a[2] = $a[1] - $a[0];
              $b[2] = $b[1] - $b[0];
              $c[2] = $c[1] - $c[0];
              Context("LimitedPolynomial-Strict");
              $revenue = Formula("$a[1] x^2 + $b[1]x + $c[1]")->reduce;
              $cost = Formula("$a[0] x^2 + $b[0]x + $c[0]")->reduce;
              $profit = Formula("$a[2] x^2 + $b[2]x + $c[2]")->reduce;
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If revenue is modeled by <m><var name="$revenue"/></m> and costs are modeled by
                <m><var name="$cost"/></m>, what is the model for profit?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$profit" width="16"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="sales-polyomials-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-sales-polyomials"/>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
      <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algae</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            There are two types of algae (blue and green) growing in a pond, and each type's total
            biomass (measured in kilograms) can be modeled using a polynomial where the variable
            <m>t</m> represents time.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="algae-polyomials">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-algae-polyomials">
            <pg-code>
              @a = random_subset(2, map {$_/1000} (1 .. 9));
              @b = random_subset(2, map {$_/100} (-90 .. 90));
              @c = random_subset(2, 100 .. 200);
              $a[2] = $a[1] + $a[0];
              $b[2] = $b[1] + $b[0];
              $c[2] = $c[1] + $c[0];
              Context("LimitedPolynomial-Strict");
              $blue = Formula("$a[1] x^2 + $b[1]x + $c[1]")->reduce;
              $green = Formula("$a[0] x^2 + $b[0]x + $c[0]")->reduce;
              $total = Formula("$a[2] x^2 + $b[2]x + $c[2]")->reduce;
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If the blue algae biomass is modeled by <m><var name="$blue"/></m> and the green
                algae biomass is modeled by <m><var name="$green"/></m>, what is a model for the
                total algae biomass?
              </p>
              <p>
                <var name="$total" width="16"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="algae-polyomials-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-algae-polyomials"/>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
    </subexercises>
  </exercises>
